Arrived at Colchis, Jason is met by the enchantress Medea, daughter of king Aetes3 wh0, moved by love, secures him by her enchantments from the Dragon guarding the fleece, and from the fire-breathing bulls, with which he ploughs the appointed field, sowing it with serpents' teeth (Vll. 1-122). From these spring up armed men, who prepare to attack Jason ; buthe, instructed by Medea, casts a stone among them, whereat they perish in mutual slaughter (123-143). Returning to lolchos with Medea, be en- treats her to restore to youth his aged father.
